{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}} {{Use British English|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox stadium | name = Dudley Road | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Wolverhampton]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|52.5684|-2.1254|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1881 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1889 | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = 10,000 | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] }}
'''Dudley Road''' was a [[association football|football]] ground in [[Wolverhampton]] in [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] between 1881 and 1889, and was used during the [[1888–89 Football League|first season]] of [[the Football League]].<ref name=UD/>
==History== The ground began to be used in 1881, but had sparse facilities consisting of only a lean-to shelter on the southern touchline and a small standing area with [[duckboards]].<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p47, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> It was located to the south of Wolverhampton town centre and to the east of Dudley Road.<ref name=UD/>
Wolves were founder members of the Football League in 1888, and the first League match played at Dudley Road on 8 September 1888 was a 1–1 draw with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] watched by 2,500 spectators. The first League goal at the ground was an own goal by Villa's [[Gershom Cox]], and was thought for many years to have been the first-ever goal scored in the Football League, although modern research revealed it was actually scored at [[Pike's Lane]] by [[Kenny Davenport]] of [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>[http://www.fl125.co.uk/news/king-kenny-crowned-first-goalscorer King Kenny crowned first goalscorer] The Football League</ref> The ground's record attendance of 10,000 was set on 2 March 1889 for an [[FA Cup]] match against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]]. This was also the last match played at Dudley Road, as Wolves moved to [[Molineux Stadium]] for the start of the [[1889–90 Football League|1889–90 season]].<ref name=UD/>
The site was later used for housing, with the main road through the estate named "Wanderers Avenue".<ref name=UD/>
