{{Infobox building | name = Huey P. Long Field House | native_name = | image = Huey P. Long Field House (Baton Rouge, Louisiana).jpeg | caption = Huey P. Long Field House on the [[Louisiana State University|LSU]] campus | former_names = | building_type = | architectural_style = [[Italian Renaissance]] | structural_system = | location = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]] | owner = [[Louisiana State University]] | current_tenants = | landlord = | coordinates = {{coord|30.41506|-91.18295|format=dms|display=inline,title,source:ProprioMeOW}} | start_date = | completion_date = 1932 | demolition_date = | height = | diameter = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = | main_contractor = | architect = Weiss, Dreyfous and Seiferth | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | other_designers = | quantity_surveyor = | awards = | module ={{Infobox NRHP | name = Huey P. Long Fieldhouse | embed = yes | nrhp_type = cp | partof = [[Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge]] | partof_refnum = 88001586 | designated_nrhp_type = September 15, 1988 }} }}
'''Huey P. Long Field House''', on the campus of [[Louisiana State University]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], was constructed in 1932. It was named for notable [[U.S. Senator]] and [[Governor (United States)|state governor]] [[Huey Long]].<ref>http://www.lsu.edu/campus/locations/LFLD.html</ref> The field house is considered the original [[Student activity center|student union]] and included a [[post office]], [[ballroom]], [[gym]]nasium and also featured the largest [[swimming pool]] in the [[United States of America|United States]] at the time.<ref>http://www.lsusports.net/src/data/lsu/assets/docs/fb/pdf/03fb347-364.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=5200</ref><ref>http://www.savehpl.org/info.html</ref><ref>http://www.preservationnation.org/magazine/2009/july-august/faded-relic-reporter.html</ref>
The field house was home to the [[LSU Tigers swimming and diving|LSU Tigers]] and [[LSU Lady Tigers swimming and diving|LSU Lady Tigers]] swimming and diving teams until the [[LSU Natatorium]] was built in 1985. The former LSU [[Varsity team|varsity]] [[hockey]] team used the field house as their home venue and the former [[LSU Tigers boxing]] team also held matches at the field house in addition to [[John M. Parker Agricultural Coliseum|Parker Coliseum]].
The building is currently the home of LSU's Department of Kinesiology and School of Social Work.<ref>http://www.savehpl.org/contexture.pdf</ref>
