'''Tamara Natanovna Press'''{{#tag:ref|{{lang-ru|Тамара Натановна Пресс}}, {{lang-uk|Тамара Натанівна Пресс}}, ''Tamara Natanivna Press''|group=nb}} (born 10 May 1937) is a retired [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] athlete who dominated the shot put and discus throw in the early 1960s. She won three gold and one silver medals at the 1960 and 1964 Olympics and three European titles in 1958–1962. Between 1959 and 1965 she set 11 world records: five in the shot put and six in the discus. Domestically, she held 16 national titles, nine in the shot put (1958–66) and seven in the discus (1960–66).<ref name=ol/>

Her younger sister [[Irina Press]] was also a prominent track athlete, but mostly in the sprint events.<ref name=sr/>

==Career==
Press was born to Jewish parents in [[Kharkiv]], [[Soviet Union]]. Her father died fighting in World War II in 1942, while her mother took the daughters to [[Samarkand]], where they started training in athletics.<ref name=telegraph/><ref name="yivoencyclopedia1"/> In 1955 Press moved to Saint Petersburg to train under the renowned coach Viktor Alekseyev. Next year she was shortlisted for the Olympic team, but lost due to a strong domestic competition in the throwing events.<ref name=bio/>

==Retirement and gender rumors==
Both sisters were accused of being men or [[intersex]], and therefore sometimes  called the "Press Brothers".<ref name=telegraph/><ref>[http://www.straightdope.com/columns/080822.html "Switch hitter: If a man has a sex change can he compete in the Olympics as a woman?"] [[thestraightdope.com]]. 22 August 2008</ref><ref>[http://transgriot.blogspot.co.uk/2011/11/olympic-gender-drama-press-sisters.html Olympic Gender Drama-The Press Sisters]. TransGriot. 9 November 2011</ref> They retired in 1966, before [[Gender verification in sports|gender verification]] became mandatory on location. In retirement Press worked as an athletics coach and official in Moscow.<ref name=sr/> She also wrote several books on sport, social and economical subjects. In 1974 she defended a PhD in [[pedagogy]].<ref name=ol/> She was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]] (1960), [[Order of the Badge of Honour]] (1964) and [[Order of Friendship]] (1997).<ref name=bio/><ref name=bse/>

